1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,664
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:19,251 --> 00:00:33,235
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,442 --> 00:00:38,744
I just thought this evening I'd

4
00:00:40,143 --> 00:00:55,418
try to make some connections between the practice we're doing and daily life, and to somehow do that by going through the Eightfold Noble Path, which some of you will know by heart.

5
00:00:55,439 --> 00:00:57,360
The first is this right understanding.

6
00:00:57,481 --> 00:01:03,567
So when the Buddha talks about right understanding, he's talking about what we were discussing this morning.

7
00:01:03,817 --> 00:01:06,320
and beginning to see things as they really are.

8
00:01:07,081 --> 00:01:17,733
So that quality of transience, you see, that quality of impermanence, we tend to sit and then we get up and we forget about it and get on with life.

9
00:01:19,456 --> 00:01:22,078
And in a sense, that doesn't allow it to seep through.

10
00:01:22,138 --> 00:01:27,564
It doesn't allow the small insights we might get when we're sitting to actually, you know, dig deep.

11
00:01:28,894 --> 00:01:38,664
One thing that you might try is to set a day in which you keep reminding yourself to be aware that everything is actually passing away.

12
00:01:39,748 --> 00:01:42,194
It's easy for us to see the beginning of things.

13
00:01:42,715 --> 00:01:49,103
To see the beginning of things for us, the word new, you see, is something we're quite aware of.

14
00:01:49,805 --> 00:01:53,250
But to see the ending of things, you know, like what happened to the old pop stars?

15
00:01:53,650 --> 00:01:57,816
Actually, we know they're all coming back, aren't they?

16
00:01:57,837 --> 00:01:58,578
It's a bad example.

17
00:02:00,140 --> 00:02:08,671
It's like the ending of things isn't something we like to particularly see because, of course, it connects us with our own ending, you see.

18
00:02:10,137 --> 00:02:16,223
But to wake up in the morning and to begin to recognize that something has finished, something has gone.

19
00:02:17,344 --> 00:02:24,533
You close the door of the house before you leave and you notice that all that time spent getting up and getting out has gone, it's finished.

20
00:02:24,554 --> 00:02:25,033
Where is it?

21
00:02:26,855 --> 00:02:32,802
People come in and out of your vision, you have a chat and they go, and then you stop and you think, that's gone, that's finished.

22
00:02:33,931 --> 00:02:37,635
What we normally do is, as soon as something's finished, we're off onto something new.

23
00:02:38,056 --> 00:02:49,289
We don't recollect, we don't actually notice that something's actually gone, finished, kaput, dead, like Monty Python's parrot is finished.

24
00:02:50,211 --> 00:02:55,837
And it's bringing that consciousness to mind all the time, that things are finishing, finishing, finishing.

25
00:02:57,387 --> 00:03:07,859
Because we're always aware of the newness of things, because we always make that quick link into something new, something else, there comes that delusion of continuity, you see.

26
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:19,932
We don't actually see that things are discontinuous, that there is a rising and a passing away, and that that passing away is really a full stop before something else can happen.

27
00:03:21,074 --> 00:03:25,098
I mean, without that, you couldn't, presumably, you couldn't get creativity in the universe.

28
00:03:25,736 --> 00:03:37,556
But for us, that's a frightening point, because we see things arising, we see things arising, we're always on that little excitement, we're always looking forward to something coming.

29
00:03:38,296 --> 00:03:40,300
We're never looking back to see something going.

30
00:03:41,603 --> 00:03:52,419
When you stand at a river and you're on a bridge, you see, just look one way, the way the river's flowing, and just catch how you feel about that, what effect it has on you.

31
00:03:53,057 --> 00:04:20,279
flowing away from you and then turn around and see it coming towards you and just see how you feel about that and they're two very different positions on the same bridge and if there's a puddle somewhere just look into that there's still there's still water and see how you feel about that so this quality of an itch is called transience impermanence you can't just leave it when you get up it's got to be just part of the way we see things

32
00:04:21,711 --> 00:04:24,735
Now when you do begin to see the ending of things, what comes up, you see?

33
00:04:24,754 --> 00:04:26,156
Well, there's a lot of fear.

34
00:04:28,158 --> 00:04:29,059
You might panic even.

35
00:04:30,821 --> 00:04:33,384
I'm not putting you off.

36
00:04:33,403 --> 00:04:38,988
But there's fear there because we've never looked, we've never really accepted that things totally and utterly disappear.

37
00:04:40,050 --> 00:04:51,482
Last weekend I was, last weekend, middle of the week, Thursday, I was at a funeral for the head monk, you see, who was the chief monk at the London Bihara after a very long illness.

38
00:04:53,166 --> 00:05:01,620
And looking at the corpse, because they had him lying in state, just looking at the corpse, I could see my mind making that face move.

39
00:05:02,781 --> 00:05:07,329
I was putting life back into something which was dead, it was gone.

40
00:05:08,110 --> 00:05:14,298
And I can see how it's difficult to accept that what you're looking at is nothing.

41
00:05:14,540 --> 00:05:18,045
There's no difference between the coffin it's in and what it is.

42
00:05:18,646 --> 00:05:20,067
It's lifeless, it's gone.

43
00:05:21,060 --> 00:05:22,863
And so that's what the mind's always doing.

44
00:05:23,384 --> 00:05:32,497
Now when we say the mind, we're talking about the way it creates pictures, the way it creates stories, the way it's always creating a future for us.

45
00:05:33,740 --> 00:05:36,163
But of course the question is why?

46
00:05:36,264 --> 00:05:37,625
Why is it doing that, you see?

47
00:05:38,906 --> 00:05:43,654
And then you get down to this idea of a self, this idea of who I am.

48
00:05:43,694 --> 00:05:48,721
And this I am, when you look at it and you begin to define it,

49
00:05:48,937 --> 00:06:10,103
you find it is locked into this life form I am me you see when you start defining that in the way that other people might define you're talking about character personality your job your friendships is all me me you see now once we've taken that position in a sense

50
00:06:10,942 --> 00:06:16,528
we're in a very unfortunate place because this me wants to be happy.

51
00:06:16,870 --> 00:06:17,930
That's the drive, isn't it?

52
00:06:18,211 --> 00:06:23,918
I don't think anybody would deny that at the deepest level we'd like to just be happy.

53
00:06:24,538 --> 00:06:28,523
You know, that's basically accepted by all philosophies, whether they dream of heaven or whatnot.

54
00:06:29,363 --> 00:06:30,846
The idea is I want to be happy.

55
00:06:31,266 --> 00:06:33,187
Whatever that might mean, I just want to be happy.

56
00:06:34,790 --> 00:06:40,697
So now I'm in this world, I'm in this body, I'm in this world around me, and I've got to make it work.

57
00:06:41,302 --> 00:06:47,769
So you can see how quickly the idea of making something work begins to be a collection of things that make me happy.

58
00:06:48,610 --> 00:06:53,297
That collection is the attachment to things, you see.

59
00:06:53,416 --> 00:06:55,500
It's the gathering of things, the accumulation.

60
00:06:57,362 --> 00:07:01,466
Now, once I've got all these things, well, I've got to watch out for people who might take them away.

61
00:07:02,228 --> 00:07:07,814
So immediately, as soon as I hold on to something, I'm in a state of conflict with the world.

62
00:07:09,279 --> 00:07:13,326
Even if it's a vase, which nobody wants, nobody would ever want, it may break.

63
00:07:13,586 --> 00:07:16,512
So I've got to be especially careful that it isn't broken.

64
00:07:17,995 --> 00:07:22,521
See, as soon as you hold on to something, whether you like it or not, you're in a state of conflict.

65
00:07:24,064 --> 00:07:30,154
So, recognizing that the conflict is there, and the conflict has this two-edge.

66
00:07:30,175 --> 00:07:34,663
It's either one where you have to annihilate the opposition or run from it.

67
00:07:35,216 --> 00:07:41,449
In the Pali word, it's the Pali word, this is all included in one word, tanha.

68
00:07:41,529 --> 00:07:45,418
And you can translate it perhaps easily as wanting, not wanting.

69
00:07:45,557 --> 00:07:55,959
But it doesn't get the full force of that without recognizing that there are these three positions that we take of accumulation, rejection, annihilating something and running for it.

70
00:07:57,862 --> 00:08:00,447
Now, you have to bring that into your daily life.

71
00:08:00,807 --> 00:08:08,180
You see, it's all right sitting here and noticing that when a beautiful thought comes up, one wants to begin to develop it, to begin a story around it.

72
00:08:08,762 --> 00:08:14,451
When something unpleasant turns up, like anxiety or something, you can see that you don't look at that.

73
00:08:14,531 --> 00:08:17,576
You want to get over here somewhere, constantly pushing away.

74
00:08:19,057 --> 00:08:27,127
But you have to bring that into your daily life from the moment you get up to going through, like when you arrive at work, it might be there's just that sickly feeling.

75
00:08:28,430 --> 00:08:28,850
Not always.

76
00:08:28,870 --> 00:08:32,054
And you have to acknowledge that.

77
00:08:32,215 --> 00:08:39,884
Sometimes we just brush it aside, but it's actually being with all the stuff that's coming up, which is manifesting to us this delusion.

78
00:08:40,708 --> 00:08:41,429
That's the point.

79
00:08:42,350 --> 00:08:50,399
All this negativity, all this attachment, all that, they're the measure of our delusion, how the delusion manifests for us, you see.

80
00:08:51,160 --> 00:09:09,601
And it's by being in contact with that throughout the day, which, as it were, throws you into this other position, a position which you've discovered in your meditation, of just coexisting peacefully with these states of mind, not allowing them to hijack your life, not allowing them to overpower you, you see.

81
00:09:12,096 --> 00:09:18,647
So all this business that we're doing here of observing that, we have to find a way of bringing it into our daily life.

82
00:09:19,327 --> 00:09:26,119
And again, you can set yourself a day that this day I'll just notice how greedy I am.

83
00:09:26,139 --> 00:09:29,464
I'll just day I'll notice how irritated I've become at the smallest things.

84
00:09:30,966 --> 00:09:34,932
Because these things become habitual, we're inured to them, you see.

85
00:09:36,058 --> 00:09:41,265
We're not actually in contact with the feelings as they come up in their rawness.

86
00:09:41,986 --> 00:09:44,831
We're always just looking askance, looking away from them.

87
00:09:44,851 --> 00:09:46,634
And you keep going, you see.

88
00:09:47,735 --> 00:09:50,399
But remember that these things have a life of their own.

89
00:09:50,559 --> 00:09:52,982
They're an energy, they're a force within the psyche.

90
00:09:53,965 --> 00:10:00,514
And we know from our own blessed Freud that these things creep out in the most unfortunate ways.

91
00:10:01,642 --> 00:10:06,129
And the way you say things, slippers of the tongue and things like that, you know, very embarrassing.

92
00:10:07,230 --> 00:10:16,465
So it's that, it's that, and these, you know, it's actually becoming much more aware of that, taking your meditation, taking that awareness into daily life, you see.

93
00:10:21,131 --> 00:10:26,399
This business of anatta, you see, not self, what does that mean, not self, you know.

94
00:10:26,836 --> 00:10:28,979
Well, the simplest of things, the simplest of things.

95
00:10:29,438 --> 00:10:33,403
Like you take your socks off and you find that your toenails are grown.

96
00:10:33,423 --> 00:10:35,846
Who grew them?

97
00:10:35,866 --> 00:10:36,807
Did you have anything to do with it?

98
00:10:39,191 --> 00:10:39,672
It was just there.

99
00:10:39,692 --> 00:10:42,075
I mean, you cut them a while back and now they're back.

100
00:10:44,236 --> 00:10:45,317
You never felt it grow.

101
00:10:47,041 --> 00:10:49,062
But you insist, this is my toenail.

102
00:10:50,292 --> 00:10:55,539
But then you cut it off and it's lying there and you forget about it and somebody says, is that your toenail?

103
00:10:56,039 --> 00:10:59,105
And you've still got it, even though it's on the piece, it's still my toenail.

104
00:11:03,130 --> 00:11:05,955
And it's looking into the body and just asking yourself, what do you know?

105
00:11:05,995 --> 00:11:08,999
See the body, do you know what your liver's doing now?

106
00:11:10,542 --> 00:11:17,532
Have you ever really experienced the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the lungs?

107
00:11:19,687 --> 00:11:22,731
And yet we have this peculiar feeling that this is my body.

108
00:11:23,513 --> 00:11:26,538
But when you investigate it, you find that you hardly know anything.

109
00:11:26,557 --> 00:11:30,043
You hardly experience anything of your body, apart from when it hurts and tickles.

110
00:11:30,884 --> 00:11:31,264
That's it.

111
00:11:33,047 --> 00:11:39,897
And when we talk about self, there's an understanding there of some sort of control, an agent.

112
00:11:40,437 --> 00:11:43,020
I'm in charge.

113
00:11:43,041 --> 00:11:45,644
And then suddenly you're ill. We didn't decide that.

114
00:11:47,092 --> 00:11:51,962
And it's catching the fact that the control we have over the body is minimal.

115
00:11:52,163 --> 00:11:52,965
It's like a car.

116
00:11:53,605 --> 00:11:58,456
You can take it left, you can go right, you can go fast and forward, but you can't do anything about the wearing of the tyres.

117
00:11:59,739 --> 00:12:01,623
If the engine blows up, that's the way it is.

118
00:12:02,804 --> 00:12:05,671
If the oil starts leaking out, how do you know?

119
00:12:05,831 --> 00:12:07,735
You only know when the engine stops.

120
00:12:10,027 --> 00:12:18,375
So when you look into yourself and you begin to investigate these things, then you get that feeling of being a sort of an alien within your own body.

121
00:12:18,855 --> 00:12:19,456
Very strange.

122
00:12:20,378 --> 00:12:23,140
And again there might be a little fright comes up, you see.

123
00:12:24,081 --> 00:12:31,308
Now all that fright, all that fear that comes up around this, all that not wanting, that ignoring, is a measure of the delusion.

124
00:12:31,349 --> 00:12:35,533
That's how the delusion manifests to us.

125
00:12:35,553 --> 00:12:38,716
You might glibly say, oh well I'm not afraid of death, you see.

126
00:12:39,304 --> 00:12:42,068
I'm afraid of dying, but I'm not afraid of death.

127
00:12:43,551 --> 00:12:46,174
But you haven't a clue till you're up against it.

128
00:12:48,558 --> 00:12:49,259
It's a horrible thing.

129
00:12:49,679 --> 00:12:53,065
Because everything you think you are seems to be coming to an end.

130
00:12:53,546 --> 00:12:54,067
Completely.

131
00:12:54,086 --> 00:12:59,335
It's like they asked of the old rich woman, how much did she leave?

132
00:13:00,756 --> 00:13:01,498
He said, everything.

133
00:13:04,616 --> 00:13:10,183
And it is grasping that, it is grasping the fact that, you know, when you come across death, you see.

134
00:13:10,624 --> 00:13:15,350
Now, if you look at any spiritual tradition, they always have that contemplation.

135
00:13:16,171 --> 00:13:18,653
In medieval times, they used to have a little momentum aura, didn't they?

136
00:13:18,673 --> 00:13:22,639
A little skull on the desk, just to remind them that there was an end to things.

137
00:13:24,100 --> 00:13:27,924
Now, that contemplation of death is very much part of the practice.

138
00:13:29,373 --> 00:13:44,649
The main scripture on how to do this practice, the Satipatthana discourse, the discourse on how to establish right mindfulness, there's a whole section there about looking at dead bodies, corrupt and disappear into little bits of dust.

139
00:13:44,668 --> 00:13:45,289
A whole section.

140
00:13:46,171 --> 00:13:53,658
It says, and the commentary says you have to go to one of these charnel grounds, because in those days they just left the body out in the open and the animals and birds ate it.

141
00:13:53,807 --> 00:13:55,570
And you're supposed to just watch this process.

142
00:13:55,710 --> 00:14:00,075
And as you're watching it, you're supposed to be saying, as that body is, this body will be.

143
00:14:00,096 --> 00:14:02,698
A bit frightening, eh?

144
00:14:04,421 --> 00:14:06,984
And it gives a nice little direction not to sit wingward.

145
00:14:09,706 --> 00:14:14,753
Very detailed description on how to do meditation on a rotting dead body.

146
00:14:18,208 --> 00:14:39,990
So these three characteristics, you see, the sense of impermanence, everything stopping, everything coming to an end, the idea of possession, the idea of me, and this idea of control, and to actually bring it in as a daily practice.

147
00:14:41,591 --> 00:14:44,654
And that's how your meditation begins to seep through your life, you see.

148
00:14:46,897 --> 00:14:49,120
Now that's the negative side, that's all the horrible bit.

149
00:14:49,961 --> 00:14:54,166
The other side is the right attitude, getting the right attitude.

150
00:14:55,326 --> 00:15:00,634
So as we said this morning, whenever we sit in meditation, there is some purification going on.

151
00:15:01,173 --> 00:15:08,043
Something is exhausting itself, even if we can only weigh it in nanograms.

152
00:15:09,063 --> 00:15:13,950
Now there has to be that little effort to change it, to move it towards the positive side.

153
00:15:15,381 --> 00:15:31,486
I was telling somebody just in the last break that a woman came to me and said that her partner complained that every time she sat, she did a sitting, she was cold and not responsive, poor man.

154
00:15:33,110 --> 00:15:35,734
And I asked her, I said, well, what do you do?

155
00:15:35,774 --> 00:15:37,196
I said, you just sit and then get up.

156
00:15:37,216 --> 00:15:38,457
She said, yeah.

157
00:15:38,477 --> 00:15:38,859
I said, well, no.

158
00:15:38,918 --> 00:15:39,961
I said, you've got to do the metta.

159
00:15:40,481 --> 00:15:42,063
See, somehow you've got to reconnect.

160
00:15:42,971 --> 00:15:47,653
So when you sit, you've taken this very special position within yourself of being the observer.

161
00:15:48,336 --> 00:15:51,732
To do that, you've got to create this sort of distance.

162
00:15:52,152 --> 00:15:57,217
And that distance, if you maintain it, you see, can become slightly calloused.

163
00:15:57,519 --> 00:16:05,369
You can sometimes confuse equanimity with a lack of connection with something.

164
00:16:06,549 --> 00:16:08,712
But equanimity is a receptivity.

165
00:16:08,932 --> 00:16:10,394
It's a complete receptivity.

166
00:16:11,015 --> 00:16:13,078
So you are supposed to be connected.

167
00:16:13,759 --> 00:16:21,990
But because we take this position within ourselves of pointing and noting things, sometimes we pull back too far, you see.

168
00:16:22,256 --> 00:16:27,360
pull back too far, and we get into this position of not being able to reconnect.

169
00:16:29,363 --> 00:16:37,370
A story that I like to tell around this is that I turned up to visit one monk, and there was a cat playing with a dead mouse.

170
00:16:37,409 --> 00:16:38,850
I mean, the cat had already killed it.

171
00:16:39,631 --> 00:16:42,754
And I asked him, I said, why don't you stop that?

172
00:16:43,576 --> 00:16:45,297
And he said, well, it's cat karma.

173
00:16:45,356 --> 00:16:46,197
It's mouse karma.

174
00:16:46,758 --> 00:16:47,538
That's what they do.

175
00:16:47,619 --> 00:16:49,801
It's nothing to do with me.

176
00:16:50,380 --> 00:16:50,981
I'm just a monk.

177
00:16:52,597 --> 00:16:56,261
I went to another monastery, I was just staying there, and something quite wonderful happened.

178
00:16:56,302 --> 00:16:58,644
This cat suddenly leapt out and jumped on this bird.

179
00:16:59,504 --> 00:17:09,276
And this monk got up as quick as lightning, gave this cat one hell of a thump, and took the bird out of his mouth and held it up and realized it was killed, the lungs had been punctured.

180
00:17:09,296 --> 00:17:13,961
So he held it up in the air and he chanted, all things arise and pass away in the parlor, you see.

181
00:17:13,980 --> 00:17:15,923
All compounded things arise and pass away.

182
00:17:16,762 --> 00:17:18,786
So you see, we have a distinction here.

183
00:17:19,027 --> 00:17:28,162
What this other monk didn't recognize about the cat and the mouse was that his consciousness, his awareness was also part of that karma.

184
00:17:28,182 --> 00:17:36,155
So he's unable to connect, you see, because he's found this place of equanimity, which has actually become very dry, very unconnected.

185
00:17:37,367 --> 00:17:46,699
Now, I'm not suggesting that that would happen when somebody is meditating, say, in the morning and the evening, because daily life drags you into connection, whether you like it or not.

186
00:17:46,719 --> 00:17:52,727
But what we can do is, as it were, prepare ourselves for the day of doing this Metta practice.

187
00:17:54,568 --> 00:17:59,915
Now, what Metta does is it gives us a basic relationship to people.

188
00:18:00,576 --> 00:18:02,479
And the best word for it is goodwill.

189
00:18:02,798 --> 00:18:06,784
I know it's sometimes translated as loving kindness, but that's a bit sloppy for me.

190
00:18:08,721 --> 00:18:12,087
It's more like getting your intentions right.

191
00:18:12,147 --> 00:18:14,291
What are your intentions towards people?

192
00:18:15,394 --> 00:18:19,059
Now, supposing you're having difficulty with somebody at work, you see.

193
00:18:20,102 --> 00:18:24,690
Normally speaking, what people do is they stir it, don't they?

194
00:18:25,750 --> 00:18:28,135
They sort of stir it round and round inside themselves.

195
00:18:28,175 --> 00:18:34,205
They sort of boil gently, you know, and then they're ready for a good punch-up when they walk into work.

196
00:18:35,266 --> 00:19:04,564
now if you see that that's doing nothing apart from just creating a lot of heat and you turn that heat through the metta into a way of open-heartedness towards that person now you know that we're very sensitive to the way people look at us from quite a distance you know you can tell somebody walking down towards you whether they're going to greet you with a smile or not it's already in their body language

197
00:19:05,759 --> 00:19:29,184
